Legs (
Figs. 46, 48
) long and slender; procoxae subglobose, mesocoxae oval, metacoxae strongly transverse; metatrochanters relatively long; all femora strongly clavate; tibiae and tarsi long and slender.

Aedeagus (
Figs. 49–56
) elongate and darkly sclerotized, relatively thick-walled, with symmetrical median lobe but strongly asymmetrical and complicated subapical assemblage of internal sclerites; parameres free and slender, with apical setae.

Composition and distribution. Two species of
Leascydmus
are known from south-eastern Australia (Victoria and New South Wales ;
Fig. 194
).
